WEBVTT

1
00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:26.320
Mr. Luthor. what can I
do for you today?

2
00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:28.720
I want to close all my accounts.

3
00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:31.960
May I ask why?

4
00:00:32.120 --> 00:00:35.720
- Is there a problem?
- No. No. of course not.

5
00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:40.760
It's just that the Luthors
have been banking here for 12 years.

6
00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:44.920
- It's quite a shock.
- I'd like it all in cash.

7
00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:48.400
We'll do our best.

8
00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:53.960
- Can I get your signature?
- Certainly.

9
00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:20.240
Mr. Luthor...

10
00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:24.760
...may I see your driver's license. please?

11
00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:27.240
Why?

12
00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:31.120
This signature doesn't match our records.
I just need to verify your ID.

13
00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:34.200
I'm standing right here in front of you.
What more do you need?

14
00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:36.640
I'm sorry. It's bank policy.

15
00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:39.160
I need the money now.

16
00:01:41.520 --> 00:01:43.160
Fill the bag!

17
00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:56.240
Lex. what's going on?

18
00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.120
Get out of my way!

19
00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:35.360
Tina. where did you get this?

20
00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:38.200
Promised I'd solve all of our problems.

21
00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:41.560
Please tell me
you didn't rob the bank yesterday.

22
00:02:42.040 --> 00:02:43.280
I didn't.

23
00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:51.720
Lex Luthor did.

24
00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:56.200
Stop it. Stop it. Tina. You promised
that you wouldn't do that anymore.

25
00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:59.280
- I did it for us.
- Somebody could have gotten hurt!

26
00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:02.720
Mom. I'm fine. Now we can
afford to have the perfect life.

27
00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:06.360
- Tina. nobody's life is perfect.
- Lana's is.

28
00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:09.120
Stealing isn't the way
to solve our problems.

29
00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:11.840
I'm taking it back.
I'll say I found it in a dumpster.

30
00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:14.320
No. Mom. come on!
We deserve to be happy!

31
00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:15.640
Come on!

32
00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:23.360
Mom!

33
00:03:45.560 --> 00:03:47.160
911 emergency.

34
00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:50.240
Hello. is anyone there?

35
00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:53.960
Hello. Hello. is anyone there?

36
00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:55.920
Sorry.

37
00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:58.560
It's nothing.

38
00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:03.920
X-Rays

39
00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:58.080
This is incredible. Why would
Lex Luthor need to rob a bank?

40
00:04:58.240 --> 00:05:02.320
I've seen some pretty strange things in
my day. but this definitely takes the cake.

41
00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:03.520
Well. almost.

42
00:05:03.680 --> 00:05:06.000
He got away with $ 100.000.

43
00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:07.840
I know Lex. It wasn't him.

44
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.600
Clark. I know that he's a friend of yours.
but you saw him with your own eyes.

45
00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:13.280
I don't know what I saw.

46
00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:16.720
There must be some kind of reasonable
explanation for this. I hope.

47
00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:20.040
Me too. I'd hate to think
I have an evil twin.

48
00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:23.040
Lex. we didn't hear you pull up.

49
00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:26.200
May I come in?
I promise I'm not packing heat.

50
00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:28.720
Lex. how come you're not in jail?

51
00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:33.040
Because I was hosting a reception for 200
fertilizer distributors in Metropolis...

52
00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:36.040
...at the time of the robbery.
- The police have any leads?

53
00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:39.840
None. That's why I wanted to talk to you.
Your name was on the witness list.

54
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.400
- Did you actually see this person?
- Yeah. he looked just like you.

55
00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:46.280
Except his fingerprints and signature
didn't match mine.

56
00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:49.400
Are you sure your eyes
weren't playing tricks on you?

57
00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:51.600
What's gonna happen now?

58
00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:53.600
Hopefully. the money will turn up.

59
00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:56.320
In the meantime.
the tabloids will have a field day.

60
00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:01.080
I'm sure certain people's opinions of me
will be cemented in stone.

61
00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:02.720
I gotta get to work.

62
00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:08.960
I'm sorry you got thrown
through that window.

63
00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:12.320
- I promise. I'm not a criminal mastermind.
- I know.

64
00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:15.160
A criminal mastermind
would have worn a mask.

65
00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:27.360
Come on. Move it. That's the stuff.
Come on. you can do it. Hustle.

66
00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:31.600
Get on up there. Get on up there.
You can do it. That's the stuff.

67
00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:33.440
Let's go. Come on.

68
00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:39.520
Let's go. Hustle. hustle. hustle.

69
00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:42.160
Let's go. Let's go. Come on.

70
00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:45.240
Keep your eyes in your head. man.

71
00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:47.800
Kent!

72
00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:49.600
Are we boring you?

73
00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:53.000
I'm sorry. My head hurts.

74
00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:54.880
You need to get some blood pumping.

75
00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:57.160
You and Ross are next.
Come on down. boys.

76
00:06:57.800 --> 00:06:59.720
Come on. Put a little muscle into it.

77
00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:01.800
Ross beats you. it's 10 laps.

78
00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:05.200
Come on. Clark. Let's go.
Move it. move it.

79
00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:07.160
Looks like someone's doing laps.

80
00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:12.840
Clark. man. what's wrong?

81
00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:16.800
Clark. man. what's wrong?

82
00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:18.560
Clark!

83
00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:22.800
Kent. are you all right?
Kent. what happened up there?

84
00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.400
So when you have these flashes. you can
see through anything? People. objects?

85
00:07:53.560 --> 00:07:56.280
Sometimes I see through things.
Other times. it's like an x-ray.

86
00:07:56.440 --> 00:07:58.200
There's no warning?
This just happens?

87
00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:00.360
Well. I get a headache.
and then it hits me.

88
00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:03.360
The first time. I thought I was
hallucinating. Then it happened again.

89
00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:05.880
Clark. I'm sure there's some way
to control this.

90
00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:09.520
You guys. I can see through things.
How do you control that?

91
00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:12.960
You gotta practice. Clark. Your eyes
have muscles just like your legs.

92
00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:15.120
Your mom is right. son.

93
00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:17.920
All you have to do is
you have to figure out a way...

94
00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:20.880
...to condition them so that
you don't get these random flashes.

95
00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:22.720
That sounds great.

96
00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:24.840
How am I gonna do that?

97
00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:34.240
Lana. you have a visitor.

98
00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:36.040
Hey. Lana.

99
00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:38.920
Tina. I didn't see you at school today.
Is everything okay?

100
00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:42.040
Yeah. My mom's not feeling well.

101
00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:44.280
But she's better. so...

102
00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:50.400
So you quit cheerleading
and Nell banishes you to the garage.

103
00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:53.920
She's got clutter issues.
I'm trying to help resolve them.

104
00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:57.160
- She's forgiven you for quitting the squad?
- Not yet.

105
00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:01.640
Well. at least now you have some more
time for your unpopular friends.

106
00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:04.240
Tina. you're not unpopular.

107
00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:09.000
What happened to the girl who didn't
care what people thought about her?

108
00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:10.640
She went to high school.

109
00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:14.600
At least your mom doesn't try
to run your life.

110
00:09:15.920 --> 00:09:19.160
You know. you're lucky
that Nell cares about you.

111
00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:22.080
If something were to happen to my mom...

112
00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:23.680
...nobody would take me in.

113
00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:27.080
I'd probably be shipped off
to a foster home or something.

114
00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:31.160
- Thanks for that burst of cheer.
- Well. what do you want me to say?

115
00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:33.440
You have the perfect life.

116
00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:35.720
You want it? You can have it.

117
00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:39.280
I'd settle for the outfit.

118
00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.640
Wouldn't it be cool if we were sisters?

119
00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:49.720
If anything happened to my mom.
do you think that Nell would adopt me?

120
00:09:49.880 --> 00:09:52.040
Tina. nothing's gonna happen
to your mom.

121
00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:30.200
Did it happen again?

122
00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:33.680
- Let's go home.
- No. I'm okay.

123
00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:36.760
Didn't you need to go
to the antique store?

124
00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:41.520
Hello?

125
00:10:46.280 --> 00:10:49.360
Mrs. Kent... I mean. Martha.
How are you?

126
00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:52.200
- Good. How's business?
- Couldn't be better.

127
00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:55.600
I'm doing so many sales in Metropolis.
I'm thinking of selling the place.

128
00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:58.360
That would be a shame.
I thought you loved this store.

129
00:10:58.520 --> 00:11:01.880
Not really. I never wanted this life.
It just kind of happened.

130
00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:03.760
Is Tina around?
I thought I saw her come in.

131
00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:06.760
She's at Lana's.
They're inseparable these days.

132
00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:10.200
- Really? I could have sworn that...
- You must be seeing things.

133
00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:14.160
I need some air.
I'm gonna go for a walk.

134
00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:19.560
- I came by to pick up the lamp.
- Lamp?

135
00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:22.960
The one you were restoring for Jonathan?

136
00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:26.440
Oh. yes. Silly me. It's in the back.

137
00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:50.640
It's not quite ready. it's...

138
00:11:51.480 --> 00:11:54.120
I found this under the chest.

139
00:11:55.960 --> 00:11:57.600
I'm such an airhead.

140
00:11:57.960 --> 00:12:01.760
A client paid me in cash.
I've been looking for this all day.

141
00:12:01.920 --> 00:12:04.080
That's a lot of money.
You should be careful.

142
00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:08.720
Thanks. Why don't you stop
by next week. it'll be ready then.

143
00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:15.760
Mrs. Kent. you forgot your purse.

144
00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:18.440
Looks like we're both airheads today.

145
00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:21.960
Bye.

146
00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:00.320
Clark!

147
00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:12.920
Mom. are you all right?

148
00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:15.160
Clark!

149
00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:28.440
Police found the truck.
Abandoned out by the Stewart farm.

150
00:13:28.600 --> 00:13:31.120
- Did anybody else see the driver?
- No.

151
00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:33.120
I could have sworn it was you. Clark.

152
00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:35.200
I guess I'm not the only one
with a vision problem.

153
00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:37.640
I don't understand.
How did they get your keys?

154
00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:40.520
I have no idea.
I only went into the antique...

155
00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:42.840
What is it. Mom?

156
00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:46.920
Nothing. It's just that Rose Greer
was acting very strange.

157
00:13:47.080 --> 00:13:49.840
I found $5000 in cash under a dresser.

158
00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:55.360
It had a Smallville Savings and Loan band
on it. She said a customer paid her. but...

159
00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:58.040
- You think it's from the robbery?
- It crossed my mind.

160
00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:01.880
Wait. Rose took your keys. turned into
Clark. and then tried to run you down?

161
00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:05.520
- You're right. it's crazy.
- I don't think so.

162
00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:07.560
What?

163
00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:10.560
I saw a flash of Tina Greer's skeleton.

164
00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:12.560
It was weird and green.

165
00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:16.240
It didn't look human. You know.
like the ones you see in anatomy books?

166
00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:20.480
That's probably because Tina
was born with a soft-bone disease.

167
00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:23.560
They had her on
all these experimental drugs.

168
00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:25.760
Doctors didn't believe
she'd see first grade.

169
00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:28.760
She did get better.
right around her 3rd birthday.

170
00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:31.680
Right after the meteor shower.
wasn't it?

171
00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:33.000
Yeah.

172
00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:38.640
- Clark. what do you think Tina's doing?
- I don't know.

173
00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:43.520
I saw the same weird skeleton flash
just after the robbery... I think.

174
00:14:44.480 --> 00:14:46.440
I just wish I could control this.

175
00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:50.400
What if you try focusing it.
you know. like a telescope?

176
00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:54.600
You could start with something small.

177
00:14:57.080 --> 00:15:00.440
Try to tell me what I have
in my hand right now.

178
00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:03.720
It's your pocket-knife.

179
00:15:06.160 --> 00:15:08.400
You could see through my hand.

180
00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:11.280
No. you always carry your knife
in that pocket.

181
00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:17.880
Sweetie. what's wrong?

182
00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:21.120
You lied to me about my mother.

183
00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:34.320
- May I help you?
- Roger Nixon. Metropolis Inquisitor.

184
00:16:34.480 --> 00:16:35.960
Get off my car.

185
00:16:36.120 --> 00:16:39.040
It's a hell of a picture. Lex.
It really boosted our sales.

186
00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:41.720
I've read comic books
with less fiction than your rag.

187
00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:44.040
Well. how about this?
Is this fiction?

188
00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:46.720
It's your juvenile record.
Fascinating reading.

189
00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:50.120
Must have taken a truck of your dad's
money to keep those people quiet.

190
00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:51.560
Those records are sealed.

191
00:16:51.720 --> 00:16:53.040
I'm a resourceful guy.

192
00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.560
I saw that picture yesterday.
and it got me to thinking of a follow-up.

193
00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:03.720
""Lex Luthor's Wild Youth in Metropolis. ""
Does the name Club Zero ring a bell?

194
00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:07.280
- You print one word about that. I'll sue.
- Lawsuits take years.

195
00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:10.840
The genie will be out of the bottle.
and all the people will know...

196
00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.760
...that the new and improved Lex Luthor
is nothing but a façade.

197
00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:17.560
You know what I think. Rog?

198
00:17:18.080 --> 00:17:21.440
If you wanted to print that.
it would already be in the paper.

199
00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:25.600
- I think you're looking for a payoff.
- It's a business proposition.

200
00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:28.160
$ 100.000 and these records
will disappear forever.

201
00:17:28.360 --> 00:17:31.360
I'd question your integrity.
but you're a journalist.

202
00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:35.280
Did your father really think
he could hide you here forever?

203
00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.920
You've got 24 hours.
and this hits the front page.

204
00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:51.640
Lana. I didn't lie to you.

205
00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:55.160
I told you your mother would have been
proud of you. and she would have.

206
00:17:55.480 --> 00:17:57.000
She loved you.

207
00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:01.440
You told me a fairy tale
about a woman who led the perfect life.

208
00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:03.400
But that life was a lie.

209
00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:07.560
You said she loved cheerleading.
She hated it. but was afraid to quit.

210
00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:10.800
She didn't want to stay in Smallville.
She wanted to see the world.

211
00:18:10.960 --> 00:18:13.200
Should I have told you
your mother was unhappy?

212
00:18:13.720 --> 00:18:15.040
I would have liked the truth.

213
00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:17.720
I told you what I thought
you could handle.

214
00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:21.960
Your mother was like any other teenager.
She had her ups and her downs.

215
00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:24.720
I feel like I spent my entire life
trying to measure up...

216
00:18:24.880 --> 00:18:27.040
...to a Laura Lang who didn't exist.

217
00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:30.520
You're reading the diary
of a 17-year-old girl.

218
00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:33.640
It's a snapshot.
It's one time in her life.

219
00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:36.120
It's like I wrote this myself.

220
00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:41.280
The truth is. your mother was the
brightest. most beautiful girl in her class.

221
00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:44.480
Do you know she was picked
to give the graduation speech?

222
00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:48.080
I guess the diary ended
before that happened.

223
00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:51.000
You should have heard the speech
she gave that day.

224
00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:53.360
What did she say?

225
00:18:54.120 --> 00:18:57.680
Everything that had been bubbling up
inside her for 18 years.

226
00:18:57.920 --> 00:19:01.040
She said she felt suffocated in Smallville.

227
00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:04.680
- Do you have a copy?
- No.

228
00:19:05.280 --> 00:19:07.600
But I'll never forget the first line.

229
00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:10.400
""I never made a difference here...

230
00:19:10.960 --> 00:19:13.600
...but maybe my children can. ""

231
00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:48.880
Hello. Clark.

232
00:19:51.080 --> 00:19:52.720
Is everything okay?

233
00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:55.640
You guys ever notice anything strange
about Tina Greer?

234
00:19:57.680 --> 00:20:01.360
Nothing that would require the intense
concentration you're exerting on her.

235
00:20:01.840 --> 00:20:05.920
The only thing weird about Tina is the
amount of time she spends idolizing Lana.

236
00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:08.160
She's practically her clone.

237
00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:11.760
Come on. Let's go.

238
00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:24.680
Lana!

239
00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:28.400
- I swear. that girl's got you LoJacked.
- How do you like the sweater?

240
00:20:29.560 --> 00:20:31.520
It's great. I've got one just like it.

241
00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:35.040
I know. I got it at the same store.
I've been going on a shopping spree.

242
00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:39.080
Look. I even found this emerald necklace
in the antique store.

243
00:20:39.240 --> 00:20:40.920
Why am I not surprised?

244
00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:44.960
See you at lunch.

245
00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:47.320
Hey. are you okay?

246
00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:51.280
I stopped by your house earlier and Nell
said you weren't in the best mood. so...

247
00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:55.080
- I'm fine. Don't worry about it.
- Good. because I need a favour.

248
00:20:55.240 --> 00:20:57.480
My mom's moving
to Metropolis full-time...

249
00:20:57.640 --> 00:20:59.960
...but she doesn't wanna pull me
out of school.

250
00:21:00.120 --> 00:21:03.560
So I was thinking I can move in
with you and Nell.

251
00:21:04.320 --> 00:21:05.880
For how long?

252
00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:09.640
I don't know. A couple months.
I mean. my mom would pay you guys.

253
00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:13.160
Trust me. money is not a problem.
Just name your price.

254
00:21:13.320 --> 00:21:16.080
I could even get a horse.
We could go riding together.

255
00:21:16.240 --> 00:21:17.800
I mean. wouldn't that be cool?

256
00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:21.280
Yeah. Just give me some time
to think about it.

257
00:21:22.040 --> 00:21:25.600
- Are you sure your mom's okay with this?
- Of course.

258
00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:27.760
She knows that we're best friends.

259
00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:30.040
It was her idea.

260
00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:33.000
Just let me run it by Nell first.
She's kind of particular...

261
00:21:33.160 --> 00:21:34.840
Nell loves me.

262
00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:38.440
Look. I don't understand.
I thought that you'd be happy.

263
00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:41.640
People even say that we look alike.
We could be sisters.

264
00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:44.840
I'm just not sure it's such a good idea.

265
00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:48.000
Okay. I see. So it was all a lie?

266
00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:50.640
You were pretending to like me.
then when I come to you...

267
00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:52.680
...in my hour of need.
you blow me off?

268
00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:55.680
- Tina. calm down.
- You should have said yes. Lana.

269
00:21:56.480 --> 00:21:58.440
It would have been perfect.

270
00:22:48.840 --> 00:22:51.400
What's your glitch. huh?
Why do you keep staring at me?

271
00:22:52.320 --> 00:22:53.720
I don't know.

272
00:22:55.280 --> 00:22:56.760
Sorry.

273
00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:06.720
- What are you doing home so early?
- Having more vision problems?

274
00:23:06.880 --> 00:23:08.440
I controlled it.

275
00:23:08.600 --> 00:23:11.600
Once. Sort of.
I concentrated. and it worked.

276
00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:13.280
- Great!
- What'd you concentrate on?

277
00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:16.240
- Tina Greer's locker.
- What did you see?

278
00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:17.920
The money from the bank robbery.

279
00:23:37.440 --> 00:23:40.480
I was just locking up. deputies.
How can I help you?

280
00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:42.880
We're looking for your daughter.

281
00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:45.400
She hasn't come home yet.
What's the problem?

282
00:23:45.640 --> 00:23:50.120
The stolen money was recovered
in her school locker this afternoon.

283
00:23:50.320 --> 00:23:51.920
You're kidding.

284
00:23:52.080 --> 00:23:53.520
My Tina?

285
00:23:53.680 --> 00:23:55.720
How could she be involved in this?

286
00:23:55.880 --> 00:23:57.840
That's what we'd like to ask her.

287
00:23:58.040 --> 00:24:00.560
Would you bring her to the station
when she gets home?

288
00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:03.720
Certainly. We'll cooperate
in any way we can.

289
00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:07.320
By the way. who told you
the money was in her locker?

290
00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:09.800
Some kid with an anonymous tip.

291
00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:19.960
Clark. what are you doing?

292
00:24:20.120 --> 00:24:23.040
I'm just trying to figure out
how much change I have inside.

293
00:24:23.200 --> 00:24:25.960
You could always take it out
and count it.

294
00:24:27.520 --> 00:24:29.480
Where's the fun in that?

295
00:24:29.720 --> 00:24:31.320
Did you hear about Tina?

296
00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:34.240
They found the money
from the robbery in her locker.

297
00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:35.880
Really?

298
00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:40.680
She actually cornered me today and asked
if she could come live with me and Nell.

299
00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:42.960
Just what you need.
a bank-robbing roommate.

300
00:24:43.120 --> 00:24:45.040
I told her it wasn't such a good idea.

301
00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:48.440
I've got enough problems with Nell
without adding more to the mix.

302
00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:51.040
I always thought you and your aunt
were really close.

303
00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:54.440
She wants me to be something I'm not.

304
00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:58.600
It's like having a dual identity.

305
00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:01.760
There's the person
that everybody sees...

306
00:25:01.920 --> 00:25:04.360
...and the person that you wanna be.

307
00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:10.480
I know the feeling.

308
00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:12.720
That's why I came here.

309
00:25:12.880 --> 00:25:16.880
I think you're the only person
who sees me for who I truly am.

310
00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:20.640
I want to thank you for that.

311
00:25:24.080 --> 00:25:27.000
- What about Whitney?
- Forget Whitney.

312
00:25:28.760 --> 00:25:33.480
I've had my eye on you.
just like you've had your eye on me.

313
00:25:40.480 --> 00:25:42.800
I don't know how you found out
about that money...

314
00:25:42.960 --> 00:25:45.800
...but you should have stayed
out of my life. Clark.

315
00:26:03.120 --> 00:26:06.200
Well. there's no sign
of Tina or Lana or...

316
00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:09.640
Are you positive you saw her
turn back into Tina?

317
00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:12.640
I think the meteor shower
did something to her bones.

318
00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:17.160
- So she can change appearance at will?
- Yeah. and it gives her strength.

319
00:26:17.320 --> 00:26:19.280
- What should we tell the police?
- Nothing.

320
00:26:19.720 --> 00:26:21.240
Tina can turn into whoever she wants...

321
00:26:21.400 --> 00:26:23.760
...and I'm the only one
who can tell the difference.

322
00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:31.640
Pete. you throw that rubber spider again
and I'm going for my staple gun.

323
00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:33.520
Mind if I come in?

324
00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:38.480
The girl who writes for the pom-pom
parade is. no surprise. out with mono.

325
00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:41.400
This week's editorial?

326
00:26:42.440 --> 00:26:46.280
My semi annual
"Where are our priorities?" rant.

327
00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:50.480
For what it's worth. I really like what
you've done with the paper this year.

328
00:26:50.760 --> 00:26:53.560
Well. that puts you
in the majority of one.

329
00:26:55.400 --> 00:26:57.040
I'm sorry about the pom-pom crack.

330
00:26:57.200 --> 00:27:00.160
Once I hit take-no-prisoners mode.
it's hard to shut it off.

331
00:27:00.320 --> 00:27:02.000
Actually. I admire it.

332
00:27:03.480 --> 00:27:05.360
You know who you are.
and you go for it.

333
00:27:06.560 --> 00:27:08.760
Well. I appreciate the compliment.

334
00:27:08.920 --> 00:27:12.440
However. I know you haven't come down
to this hole to give me a pep talk.

335
00:27:12.600 --> 00:27:15.880
The Torch prints the graduation speech
every year. right?

336
00:27:16.040 --> 00:27:19.400
Having transcribed last year's snore-fest.
that's an unfortunate yes.

337
00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:22.320
- What year?
- 1977.

338
00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:24.520
That's P.C.

339
00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:27.360
- P.C.?
- Pre-computer. When disco ruled the earth.

340
00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:29.320
Anything before then is gonna be H.C.

341
00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:32.200
- Hard copy.
- You catch on fast.

342
00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:34.720
Let's see.

343
00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:36.280
'77. here we go.

344
00:27:39.480 --> 00:27:44.360
""Saturday Night Fever"" was their prom
theme. Styx won group of the century...

345
00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:48.760
Wow. Someone got in the administration's
collective face.

346
00:27:48.920 --> 00:27:51.880
""Due to the controversial nature
of this year's graduation address...

347
00:27:52.040 --> 00:27:55.720
...the editors have elected not to run
the text in this issue of the Torch. ""

348
00:27:55.880 --> 00:27:59.280
Meaning. ironically. it's probably
the only one worth reading.

349
00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:03.840
Maybe I could track something down for
you. Do you know who gave this speech?

350
00:28:06.360 --> 00:28:08.080
My mother.

351
00:28:25.080 --> 00:28:26.480
Can I fix you a drink?

352
00:28:26.840 --> 00:28:29.200
I'd just as soon get my money
and get out.

353
00:28:29.680 --> 00:28:31.160
Of course.

354
00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:33.000
I assume I don't have to count it?

355
00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:35.640
I've even supplied the bag.

356
00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:44.600
You're feeling pretty good
about yourself right now. aren't you?

357
00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:50.280
You'd think with all the money my father
spent. he could make things disappear.

358
00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:53.520
Maybe he's not as smart as he thinks.

359
00:28:55.720 --> 00:28:57.720
The original.

360
00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:00.240
Have a nice life.

361
00:29:00.840 --> 00:29:03.720
If you walk out that door.
I will make you disappear.

362
00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:09.160
What are you going to do?
You gonna have me killed?

363
00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:13.040
No. you'll be very much alive.

364
00:29:13.480 --> 00:29:16.560
But there won't be any evidence
of your existence.

365
00:29:16.800 --> 00:29:18.240
What are you talking about?

366
00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:23.120
Driver's license. passport. social security
number. bank account. will all be erased.

367
00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:27.800
With one call. I can ensure there will be no
record that you actually walked this earth.

368
00:29:29.320 --> 00:29:30.640
You're bluffing.

369
00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:35.440
Call your bank.
See if your account still exists.

370
00:29:37.320 --> 00:29:40.360
That is. if your cell phone
hasn't already been disconnected.

371
00:29:45.840 --> 00:29:47.440
What did you do?

372
00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:51.200
Don't worry. Roger.
I'm gonna give you a new identity.

373
00:29:51.360 --> 00:29:54.000
One that's a little less upstanding.

374
00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:56.160
Maybe a murderer.

375
00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:57.560
Maybe a drug dealer.

376
00:29:57.720 --> 00:30:00.680
Either way. you lose your job.
your house and your family.

377
00:30:03.840 --> 00:30:05.680
I'll give the money back.

378
00:30:07.200 --> 00:30:08.840
Then we'll be even.

379
00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:10.440
No. we won't.

380
00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:14.400
Because I also know your brother
works for Juvenile Court.

381
00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:19.200
What'd you tell him? Steal the records
and you can make some quick cash?

382
00:30:19.360 --> 00:30:22.240
- He could do time for that.
- Leave him out of this.

383
00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:26.880
I didn't get him involved. Roger.
You did.

384
00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:31.200
You came into my life
thinking you could shake me down...

385
00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:34.760
...because I was some spoiled. rich brat
who needed his daddy's protection.

386
00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:40.960
Trust me. when I make things disappear.
they stay buried.

387
00:30:41.880 --> 00:30:43.560
What do you want from me?

388
00:30:45.080 --> 00:30:46.480
Your help.

389
00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:50.480
My father's obsessed
with the Daily Planet.

390
00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:55.120
But I know the Inquisitor's read by the
people. They're the ones I'm interested in.

391
00:30:55.600 --> 00:30:57.640
I will feed you stories.
You will print them.

392
00:30:57.800 --> 00:31:02.240
Any negative stories about me. you will
kill. You will be at my disposal. 24/7.

393
00:31:02.400 --> 00:31:04.040
Follow me.

394
00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:22.080
- What happened to your car?
- I drove it off a bridge at 60 miles an hour.

395
00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:24.920
How are you still alive?

396
00:31:25.080 --> 00:31:27.880
That's the mystery
I need your help solving.

397
00:31:52.120 --> 00:31:53.600
Clark. what's wrong?

398
00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:56.120
Why are you looking at me like that?

399
00:31:56.360 --> 00:31:59.160
Sorry. it's nothing.
I wasn't sure it was you.

400
00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:03.360
- This is a bad time.
- No.

401
00:32:06.120 --> 00:32:10.240
I was out jogging. didn't wanna go home.
kind of ended up here.

402
00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:13.400
You and Nell are still fighting.

403
00:32:13.800 --> 00:32:14.960
How'd you know?

404
00:32:16.440 --> 00:32:18.760
Just perceptive. I guess.

405
00:32:19.520 --> 00:32:21.640
Found my mother's diary.

406
00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:26.160
Discovered that a lot of the things
that I've been feeling. she felt too.

407
00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:27.560
That's great.

408
00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:32.080
Isn't it?

409
00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:36.240
It's great and it's frustrating
and it's scary.

410
00:32:36.600 --> 00:32:39.000
Like she could see right through me.

411
00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:41.400
Do you ever feel like that?

412
00:32:42.920 --> 00:32:44.240
More than you know.

413
00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:51.640
When I was reading her words.
it was like she was talking to me.

414
00:32:52.200 --> 00:32:54.280
And then she was gone.

415
00:32:55.400 --> 00:32:58.520
Well. you're lucky.
You're lucky you got at least that.

416
00:32:59.440 --> 00:33:03.840
Have you ever tried to find your parents?
Your biological parents. I mean?

417
00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:08.480
Not really. I figure they're a million years
away from my life now.

418
00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:12.400
If you could ask them a question.
what would you ask?

419
00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:18.480
What happened?
Why'd they let me go?

420
00:33:19.120 --> 00:33:23.720
How do I make sense
of all the strangeness in my life?

421
00:33:26.520 --> 00:33:29.680
I guess neither of us
will ever get a straight answer.

422
00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.480
I hope you find what you're looking for.

423
00:33:42.800 --> 00:33:44.680
I thought you were working on a project.

424
00:33:44.840 --> 00:33:49.680
I finished early. I thought I'd spend some
time with the best boyfriend in the world.

425
00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:52.440
I'd love to. but I've got
that trig test tomorrow.

426
00:33:52.600 --> 00:33:54.560
Right. I forgot.

427
00:33:54.760 --> 00:33:58.160
That's okay.
We've got the rest of our lives.

428
00:34:00.880 --> 00:34:02.520
What's gotten into you?

429
00:34:02.680 --> 00:34:05.160
It's the new me. You like?

430
00:34:05.320 --> 00:34:09.520
I definitely could get used to it.
Do you need a ride home?

431
00:34:09.680 --> 00:34:11.120
I'm covered.

432
00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:13.960
Can I borrow your jacket?
It's a little cold.

433
00:34:14.440 --> 00:34:16.520
Yeah. sure.

434
00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:19.680
I'll see you tomorrow.

435
00:34:33.880 --> 00:34:37.680
So Tina Greer can bend her bones like a
contortionist. become anyone she wants?

436
00:34:37.840 --> 00:34:39.280
I saw it with my own eyes.

437
00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:41.800
I'm sorry.
This is usually Chloe's territory.

438
00:34:41.960 --> 00:34:44.280
I cover girls. football
and general guy stuff.

439
00:34:44.440 --> 00:34:47.480
She does the tales of the unexplained.
Why not give her a call?

440
00:34:47.640 --> 00:34:49.720
I did. She said she's busy
with something else.

441
00:34:49.880 --> 00:34:52.480
That's like getting turned down
by The National Enquirer.

442
00:34:52.640 --> 00:34:53.680
Why are we friends?

443
00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.960
Because even when I think you're
whacked. I show up ready to rumble.

444
00:34:57.120 --> 00:34:58.680
Great. it's closed.

445
00:35:06.240 --> 00:35:08.800
Clark. man.
haven't you ever watched Cops?

446
00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.880
The last place Tina will hide out
is in her mom's store.

447
00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:24.440
Earth to Clark.

448
00:35:26.840 --> 00:35:29.120
- Is everything okay?
- We need to get in here.

449
00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:32.800
- Why?
- Just... It's a hunch.

450
00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:39.600
Hey. Clark. what are we looking for?

451
00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:49.360
- Who's that?
- It's Tina's mom.

452
00:35:49.520 --> 00:35:51.920
Damn. How'd you know she was in there?

453
00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:55.920
- Because I can see right through the door.
- Very funny. Sherlock.

454
00:35:56.080 --> 00:35:58.560
- How do you think she died?
- Broken neck.

455
00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:03.640
I'm guessing.

456
00:36:04.360 --> 00:36:06.760
My call. Tina's already
on a bus to Metropolis.

457
00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:11.880
I don't think so.

458
00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:18.600
Why's she writing Lana's signature?

459
00:36:18.760 --> 00:36:21.280
You said Tina was obsessed with her.

460
00:36:21.440 --> 00:36:25.200
- She's gonna take it to the next level.
- She wants to kill Lana?

461
00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:27.560
Worse. She wants to become Lana.

462
00:36:32.160 --> 00:36:36.480
Found your journal. Mom.
The one you kept in high school?

463
00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:41.200
Suddenly all these conversations
don't seem so one-sided.

464
00:36:42.240 --> 00:36:46.440
Tried to find your graduation speech.
but they didn't print it.

465
00:36:46.640 --> 00:36:51.120
Every time I get closer to you.
something pulls me away.

466
00:36:52.320 --> 00:36:53.920
Lana.

467
00:36:54.440 --> 00:36:57.800
- Whitney. what are you doing here?
- Your aunt said you went riding.

468
00:36:57.960 --> 00:36:59.440
I just followed the path.

469
00:36:59.880 --> 00:37:02.080
Just talking to my parents.

470
00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:04.280
They're dead. Lana.

471
00:37:05.640 --> 00:37:08.400
You have this great life.
and you can't even see it.

472
00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.880
You have no right to be unhappy.

473
00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:16.000
They're not coming back. Lana.
Deal with it.

474
00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:17.880
What are you saying?

475
00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:21.840
I'm saying
you don't deserve your life.

476
00:37:25.720 --> 00:37:26.760
I do.

477
00:38:09.200 --> 00:38:10.760
What are you doing here?

478
00:38:10.920 --> 00:38:13.320
I was gonna ask you the same thing.

479
00:38:14.600 --> 00:38:17.480
- Where's Lana?
- I don't know.

480
00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:21.360
Nell said she came out here.
but I can't find her.

481
00:38:25.400 --> 00:38:27.000
What's the matter. Clark?

482
00:38:27.200 --> 00:38:28.480
Not feeling well?

483
00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:38.560
- Tina. where's Lana?
- Tina doesn't exist anymore!

484
00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:48.120
I know what it's like to live with a secret.

485
00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:51.080
I know what happened to your mother.

486
00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:52.880
That was a lifetime ago.

487
00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:56.320
And don't worry about Lana.
You'll be joining her very soon.

488
00:39:00.600 --> 00:39:05.000
I thought I killed you once. I'm not
gonna make the same mistake twice.

489
00:39:07.680 --> 00:39:09.440
Where's Lana?

490
00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:17.400
Who are you?

491
00:39:21.960 --> 00:39:23.000
Where is she?

492
00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:25.560
She's dead.

493
00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:45.360
Lana!

494
00:40:37.960 --> 00:40:39.920
Hey. I heard what happened.

495
00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:42.160
Did you come by to see if I was okay?

496
00:40:42.320 --> 00:40:45.160
As concerned as I always am
about your personal well-being...

497
00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:47.280
...I'm not here to see you.

498
00:40:49.840 --> 00:40:51.040
I did some digging.

499
00:40:56.160 --> 00:40:57.480
How did you find this?

500
00:40:58.000 --> 00:40:59.680
If I told you. I'd have to kill you...

501
00:40:59.840 --> 00:41:02.680
...and it looks like you've had
enough trauma for one night.

502
00:41:03.240 --> 00:41:06.240
- Chloe. thank you.
- No problem.

503
00:41:08.120 --> 00:41:10.720
- How's Tina?
- She won't be able to hurt anyone else.

504
00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:13.120
I don't understand
why a girl would do all that.

505
00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:14.840
I do.

506
00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:18.360
You go through life
with a gift you have to keep a secret.

507
00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:21.960
When you see everyone around you
being normal. you get jealous.

508
00:41:22.120 --> 00:41:23.600
You just wanna be somebody else.

509
00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:40.880
You really like her. don't you?

510
00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:15.600
Mom. if you could see anything.
what would you do?

511
00:42:16.520 --> 00:42:18.480
Learn to close my eyes.

512
00:42:43.640 --> 00:42:47.560
As principal of Smallville High.
I would like to introduce...

513
00:42:47.720 --> 00:42:52.880
...the valedictorian of the class of 1977.
Miss Laura Potter.

514
00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:01.920
Ladies and gentlemen.
graduating seniors. good evening.

515
00:43:02.080 --> 00:43:06.520
Those familiar words open every
graduation address at Smallville High...

516
00:43:06.680 --> 00:43:08.680
...and I use them deliberately...

517
00:43:08.760 --> 00:43:12.040
...because the rest of my speech
will not be so reassuring.

518
00:43:12.120 --> 00:43:16.960
I never made a difference here.
but maybe my children can.

519
00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:20.360
When I first came to Smallville High.
I was full of hope.

520
00:43:20.680 --> 00:43:23.880
I thought the world was gonna be...

521
00:44:26.720 --> 00:44:27.760
Subtitles by
SDI Media Group

522
00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:28.960
[ENGLISH]



